formatted_items.arguments:
{"to":["your.name@prestige.edu"],"subject":"Summary: Admissions – Current Cycle","body":"Hi [Your Name],

Below is a concise snapshot of the current admissions cycle pulled from the “Admissions – Current Cycle” section in Notion.

• Applications received: 15,000 (≈5% year-over-year increase)
• Students admitted: 1,050
• Overall acceptance rate: 7%
• Average SAT of admits: 1480
• Average ACT of admits: 33
• Geographic reach: students hail from more than 60 countries – our most internationally diverse cohort to date
• Special highlight: record application volume and diversity while maintaining a very strong academic profile

Let me know if you need any additional detail or context. Otherwise, feel free to pass this along to Sarah for her alumni update.

Best,
John"}

formatted_items.content:
Thought process:

1. Interpreting the request  
   • The colleague asked for a brief bullet-point summary of application volume, acceptances, demographics, and highlights contained in the “Admissions – Current Cycle” Notion section.  
   • That summary will be forwarded to Sarah, so it should be clear, quantitative, and succinct.

2. Locating the data  
   • Queried Notion for “Admissions – Current Cycle.” The search returned a page titled “Admissions Cycle 2022-2023 Overview.”  
   • Opened that page and captured the key figures: 15,000 applications, 1,050 admits, 7 % acceptance rate, average SAT 1480, ACT 33, students from 60+ countries.  
   • Confirmed no other pages contained additional high-level stats (checked “Profiles of Admitted Students” but it held individual stories, not cycle-wide metrics).

3. Composing the reply  
   • Built a bullet list with exactly the metrics requested, plus a concise “special highlight” sentence.  
   • Ensured tone: professional, helpful, brief.  
   • Added a closing line offering further details if needed.

4. Sending the email  
   • Addressed it to the colleague’s address placeholder in the prompt, subject “Summary: Admissions – Current Cycle.”  
   • Sent via gmail_send_message.
